[src:micrometer-metrics-java/java-programming-language] James Gosling, Mike Sheridan, and Patrick Naughton initiated the Java language project in June 1991.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/java-programming-language] Java was originally designed for interactive television, but it was too advanced for the digital cable television industry at the time.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/java-programming-language] The language was initially called *Oak* after an oak tree that stood outside Gosling's office.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/java-programming-language] Later the project went by the name *Green* and was finally renamed *Java*, from Java coffee, a type of coffee from Indonesia.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/java-programming-language] Gosling designed Java with a C/C++-style syntax that system and application programmers would find familiar.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/java-programming-language] Sun Microsystems released the first public implementation as Java 1.0 in 1996.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/java-programming-language] It promised write once, run anywhere (WORA) functionality, providing no-cost run-times on popular platforms.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/java-programming-language] Fairly secure and featuring configurable security, it allowed network- and file-access restrictions.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/java-programming-language] Major web browsers soon incorporated the ability to run Java applets within web pages, and Java quickly became popular.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/java-programming-language] The Java 1.0 compiler was re-written in Java by Arthur van Hoff to comply strictly with the Java 1.0 language specification.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/java-programming-language] With the advent of Java 2 (released initially as J2SE 1.2 in December 1998 – 1999), new versions had multiple configurations built for different types of platforms.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/java-programming-language] J2EE included technologies and APIs for enterprise applications typically run in server environments, while J2ME featured APIs optimized for mobile applications.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/java-programming-language] In 2006, for marketing purposes, Sun renamed new J2 versions as *Java EE*, *Java ME*, and *Java SE*, respectively.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/java-programming-language] In 1997, Sun Microsystems approached the ISO/IEC JTC 1 standards body and later the Ecma International to formalize Java, but it soon withdrew from the process.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/java-programming-language] Java remains a *de facto* standard, controlled through the Java Community Process.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/java-programming-language] At one time, Sun made most of its Java implementations available without charge, despite their proprietary software status.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/java-programming-language] Sun generated revenue from Java through the selling of licenses for specialized products such as the Java Enterprise System.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/java-programming-language] On November 13, 2006, Sun released much of its Java virtual machine (JVM) as free and open-source software (FOSS), under the terms of the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/java-programming-language] On May 8, 2007, Sun finished the process, making all of its JVM's core code available under free software/open-source distribution terms, aside from a small portion of code to which Sun did not hold the copyright.
