[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] In software engineering, more specifically in distributed computing, **observability** is the ability to collect data about programs' execution, modules' internal states, and the communication among components.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] To improve observability, software engineers use a wide range of logging and tracing techniques to gather telemetry information, and tools to analyze and use it.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] Observability is foundational to site reliability engineering, as it is the first step in triaging a service outage.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] One of the goals of observability is to minimize the amount of prior knowledge needed to debug an issue.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] The term is borrowed from control theory, where the "observability" of a system measures how well its state can be determined from its outputs.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] Similarly, software observability measures how well a system's state can be understood from the obtained telemetry (metrics, logs, traces, profiling).
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] The term is frequently referred to as its numeronym **o11y** (where 11 stands for the number of letters between the first letter and the last letter of the word).
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] This is similar to other computer science abbreviations such as i18n and l10n and k8s.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] Observability and monitoring are sometimes used interchangeably.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] As tooling, commercial offerings and practices evolved in complexity, "monitoring" was re-branded as observability in order to differentiate new tools from the old.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] The terms are commonly contrasted in that systems are *monitored* using predefined sets of *telemetry*, and monitored systems may be *observable*.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] Majors et al. suggest that engineering teams that only have monitoring tools end up relying on expert foreknowledge (seniority), whereas teams that have observability tools rely on exploratory analysis (curiosity).
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] Observability relies on three main types of telemetry data: metrics, logs and traces.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] Those are often referred to as "pillars of observability".
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] A metric is a point in time measurement (scalar) that represents some system state.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] Monitoring tools are typically configured to emit alerts when certain metric values exceed set thresholds.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] Thresholds are set based on knowledge about normal operating conditions and experience.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] Metrics are typically tagged to facilitate grouping and searchability.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] Application developers choose what kind of metrics to instrument their software with, before it is released.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] As a result, when a previously unknown issue is encountered, it is impossible to add new metrics without shipping new code.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] Furthermore, their cardinality can quickly make the storage size of telemetry data prohibitively expensive.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] Since metrics are cardinality-limited, they are often used to represent aggregate values (for example: average page load time, or 5-second average of the request rate).
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] Without external context, it is impossible to correlate between events (such as user requests) and distinct metric values.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] Logs, or log lines, are generally free-form, unstructured text blobs that are intended to be human readable.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] Modern logging is structured to enable machine parsability.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] As with metrics, an application developer must instrument the application upfront and ship new code if different logging information is required.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] Logs typically include a timestamp and severity level.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] An event (such as a user request) may be fragmented across multiple log lines and interweave with logs from concurrent events.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] A cloud native application is typically made up of distributed services which together fulfill a single request.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] A distributed trace is an interrelated series of discrete events (also called spans) that track the progression of a single user request.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] A trace shows the causal and temporal relationships between the services that interoperate to fulfill a request.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] Instrumenting an application with traces means sending span information to a tracing backend.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] The tracing backend correlates the received spans to generate presentable traces.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] To be able to follow a request as it traverses multiple services, spans are labeled with unique identifiers that enable constructing a parent-child relationship between spans.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] Span information is typically shared in the HTTP headers of outbound requests.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] Continuous profiling is another telemetry type used to precisely determine how an application consumes resources.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] To be able to observe an application, telemetry about the application's behavior needs to be collected or exported.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] Instrumentation means generating telemetry alongside the normal operation of the application.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] Telemetry is then collected by an independent backend for later analysis.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] Instrumentation can be automatic, or custom.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] Automatic instrumentation offers blanket coverage and immediate value; custom instrumentation brings higher value but requires more intimate involvement with the instrumented application.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] Instrumentation can be native - done in-code (modifying the code of the instrumented application) - or out-of-code (e.g. sidecar, eBPF).
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] Verifying new features in production by shipping them together with custom instrumentation is a practice called "observability-driven development".
