[src:micrometer-metrics-java/observability-software] Self monitoring may be put in place in addition to high availability and redundancy to further avoid correlated failures.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] A **performance indicator** or **key performance indicator** (**KPI**) is a type of performance measurement used to evaluate the success of an organization, activity, project, or process in achieving defined objectives.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] KPIs provide a focus for strategic and operational improvement, support evidence-based decision-making, and help organizations identify and monitor factors critical to performance.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] KPIs may measure progress toward operational targets such as quality levels, efficiency, or customer satisfaction or toward broader strategic goals.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] The selection of appropriate KPIs depends on an organization’s priorities and context, and indicators often differ across functional areas such as finance, sales, operations, or human resources.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Management frameworks such as the **balanced scorecard** are commonly used to structure KPI selection and align measurement with strategy.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Performance indicators are applied across sectors including business, government, healthcare, and technical systems.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Their effectiveness depends on clear definition, reliable data, and appropriate interpretation, as poorly designed indicators may create unintended incentives or fail to capture meaningful outcomes.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] KPIs are used not only for business organizations but also for technical aspects such as machine performance.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] For example, a machine used for production in a factory would output various signals indicating how the current machine status is (e.g., machine sensor signals).
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Some signals or signals as a result of processing the existing signals may represent the high-level machine performance.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] These representative signals can be KPI for the machine.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] The effective use of performance indicators requires a clear understanding of their different types and purposes.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Indicators can be categorised along several key dimensions to ensure a balanced and comprehensive measurement system that supports strategic objectives.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] A well-designed set of indicators will draw from multiple categories to avoid unintended consequences and provide a holistic view of organisational performance.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] A primary method of categorisation is based on the **dimension of performance** being measured.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] The Balanced Scorecard framework, for instance, groups indicators into four perspectives: financial (e.g., profitability), customer (e.g., satisfaction), internal business processes (e.g., efficiency), and learning and growth (e.g., innovation).
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] This approach prevents over-reliance on financial metrics alone.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Indicators are also commonly distinguished by their **time orientation and function**.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Another critical distinction is based on the **nature of the data**.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Quantitative indicators provide objective, numerical measurement (e.g., unit output, error rates), while qualitative indicators capture subjective, often perceptual data (e.g., stakeholder satisfaction, brand reputation) typically gathered through surveys and interviews.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Furthermore, indicators can be designed for different **levels of the organisation**.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Strategic indicators monitor progress toward top-level goals, operational indicators track departmental or process efficiency, and individual indicators align personal objectives with organisational priorities.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Selecting the right mix of categories is a strategic exercise.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] An overemphasis on lagging quantitative indicators can lead to short-termism and "gaming" of metrics, while focusing solely on leading or qualitative indicators may lack a connection to ultimate outcomes.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] A balanced portfolio of indicators across these categories is therefore essential for effective performance management.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] The first step in performance measurement is determining what to measure.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Performance indictors may be applied at various stages within a programme, service, or organisational process.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] These points capture distinct dimensions of performance, ranging from the earliest stages of resource allocation to final outcomes achieved.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Mapping indicators across this continuum helps ensure measurement provides a clear picture of performance.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] The points of measurement may also relate to the relationship between inputs and outputs (productivity), and outputs and outcome (effectiveness).
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Control (the extent to which employees can influence a result) and mechanism (the causal link between employees’ effort and a performance dimension) further shape measurement decisions.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Selecting the appropriate point of measurement is not simply a technical choice but also a strategic one.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] For example, focusing narrowly on inputs or outputs can incentivise ‘box-ticking’ behaviours and obscure whether real value is being created.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Conversely, outcome and impact indicators may be harder to attribute to organisational effort, especially in complex public sector environments.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] A balanced approach can involve linking indicators across multiple points of measurement, to trace the relationships between resources, activities and ultimate value.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] However, this requires careful design to avoid measurement burdens and to ensure alignment with an organisation’s overall strategic objectives.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Quality assurance across the points of measurement helps ensure indicators not only track activity levels but also produce robust, consistent and credible performance data.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Once appropriate points of measurement have been determined, the next task is to identify specific indicators that meaningfully capture performance at that stage.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] An indicator is a measurable variable used to show whether progress is being made towards a goal, rather than the goal itself.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Choice of indicators reflects managerial decisions about what counts as successful performance.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Indicators may be financial, such as revenue growth, or non-financial, such as customer satisfaction rates.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] A good indicator should be simple to understand while aligning closely with business or organisational goals.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] The process of identifying indicators is often guided by frameworks such as SMART (specific, measurable, achievable, relevant, time-bound).
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Alternatives like the FABRIC principles emphasise ideal performance information is focused, appropriate, balanced, robust, integrated, and cost-effective.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] In the public sector, where outcomes may depend on many different organisations and external influences, careful selection is needed to avoid misleading or overly broad results.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Beyond the technical steps, several broader considerations shape indicator usefulness.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Indicators must be simple enough for managers and other stakeholders, including shareholders or the public, to understand but precise enough to capture what matters.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Over-simplified indicators may distort or fail to drive performance, while overly complex or too numerous indicators may fail to gain traction.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] In the public sector, multiple organisations may influence outcomes indicators, and may sometimes develop a shared outcomes framework with reporting to show the particular role an individual organisation.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Where a clear link exists between employee effort and performance, indicators may be connected to motivation, reward and appraisal systems.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Data quality is another important consideration.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Indicators depend on reliable and consistent information.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Weak systems can undermine credibility, shaping which indicators are ultimately preferred.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Finally, given the risks of gaming, data fabrication, and selective reporting on indictors, organisations should consider verifiability of underlying data when selecting indicators and choose indicators that are not susceptible to manipulation.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Many of these customer KPIs are developed and managed with customer relationship management software.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Faster availability of data is a competitive issue for most organizations.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] For example, businesses that have higher operational/credit risk (involving for example credit cards or wealth management) may want weekly or even daily availability of KPI analysis, facilitated by appropriate IT systems and tools.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Overall equipment effectiveness (OEE) is a set of broadly accepted nonfinancial metrics that reflect manufacturing success.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Most professional services firms (for example, management consultancies, systems integration firms, or digital marketing agencies) use three key performance indicators to track the health of their businesses.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] They typically use professional services automation (PSA) software to keep track of and manage these metrics.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Businesses can utilize supply chain KPIs to establish and monitor progress toward a variety of goals, including lean manufacturing objectives, minority business enterprise and diversity spending, environmental "green" initiatives, cost avoidance programs and low-cost country sourcing targets.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Suppliers can implement KPIs to gain a competitive advantage.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Suppliers have instant access to a user-friendly portal for submitting standardized cost savings templates.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Suppliers and their customers exchange vital supply chain performance data while gaining visibility to the exact status of cost improvement projects and cost savings documentation.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] In a warehouse, the manager will use KPIs that target best use of the facility, like the receiving and put away KPIs to measure the receiving efficiency and the putaway cost per line.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Storage KPIs can also be used to determine the efficiency of the storage space and the carrying cost of the inventory.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Governments around the world have adopted performance indicators as part of broader performance management reforms.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] These initiatives emerged from general concerns about performance deficits in the public sector, and the belief that systematic measurement could improve accountability and outcomes.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] While governments have established extensive systems for collecting performance data, research suggests that the value of these indicators depends on whether managers effectively use the information in their decision-making processes.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Factors influencing the use of performance data include individual values, leadership roles, organisational culture, and external pressures.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Managers with strong public service motivation are more likely to engage with performance information because they see it as a means of achieving public goals.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Task-specific leaders often use indicators more actively than generalist leaders who face broader political responsibilities.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Organisational cultures that emphasise learning, flexibility, and innovation are more likely to foster the use of performance information, whereas rigid or highly centralised environments may discourage it.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Citizen participation can also create demand for greater accountability, encouraging managers to apply performance data to justify decisions and demonstrate transparency.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] International examples show the diversity of approaches.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] The provincial government of Ontario, Canada has used performance indicators since the late 1990s to assess higher education institutions, reporting on measures such as graduate satisfaction, employment rates, and student outcomes.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] In England, Public Health England applies indicators to monitor national health screening programmes, while UK government departments publish key contract-related indicators to improve service transparency.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] The United States requires federal agencies to set strategic goals and report on progress under the Government Performance and Results Act.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] The New Zealand Treasury’s Living Standards Framework and associated wellbeing indicators provide a broader set of measures that move beyond economic performance to social and environmental outcomes.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Although performance indicators are now widespread, their effectiveness remains debated.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] It can be argued that indicators oversimplify complex goals, encourage symbolic compliance, and shift attention to what is easily measurable rather than what is substantively important.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] On the other hand, when well-designed and used within supportive cultures, indicators can strengthen accountability, guide learning, and improve service delivery.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Performance indicators are widely used in human resource management (HRM) to assess recruitment, retention, performance, and employee well-being.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] In the public sector, these measures are shaped by distinctive institutional constraints and workforce motivations.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Common HRM indicators include employee turnover rates, time to fill vacancies, absenteeism, staff satisfaction, and survey results.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] The effectiveness of HRM practices has been examined across public, semi-public, and private organisations.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] A large meta-analysis using the ability-motivation-opportunity (AMO) framework found that HRM practices positively influence individual performance in all sectors, but with sector-specific variations.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Ability-enhancing practices such as training and selective recruitment are consistently associated with higher job satisfaction and performance.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Motivation-enhancing practices, such as performance-based pay, show weaker impacts in public organisations, where employees are often driven more by intrinsic and altruistic motivations than extrinsic rewards.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Opportunity-enhancing practices, such as participatory decision-making and job autonomy, appear particularly important in encouraging extra-role behaviours like collaboration and knowledge-sharing.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Employee turnover is a critical indicator for HRM.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] While traditionally seen as negative, research suggests that turnover may have more complex effects.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] A study of several hundred public school districts in Texas over nine years found that turnover was linearly negative for basic educational outcomes, such as standardised test scores, but showed a non-linear “inverted U-shaped” relationship with more complex outcomes like college readiness.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] This indicates that low to moderate turnover may introduce new skills and perspectives, benefiting organisational performance, while very high turnover imposes significant costs and reduces effectiveness.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Other HRM indicators reflect absenteeism, which is often monitored as a proxy for workforce wellbeing and organisational health.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Staff satisfaction surveys are also commonly used to measure morale, commitment, and engagement, though their interpretation may be shaped by broader organisational culture and leadership practices.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Performance Indicators (PIs) are widely used to measure, manage and provide public accountability across sectors like healthcare, business, education and government.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] However, they can have challenges and limitations that may affect data accuracy, relevance, and effectiveness if not carefully considered.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] In practice, overseeing key performance indicators can prove expensive or difficult for organizations.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Some indicators such as staff morale may be impossible to quantify.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] As such, dubious KPIs can be adopted that can be used as a rough guide rather than a precise benchmark.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Key performance indicators can also lead to perverse incentives and unintended consequences as a result of employees working to the specific measurements at the expense of the actual quality or value of their work.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Sometimes, collecting statistics can become a substitute for a better understanding of the problems, so the use of dubious KPIs can result in progress in aims and measured effectiveness becoming different.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] For example, during the Vietnam War, US soldiers were shown to be effective in kill ratios and high body counts, but this was misleading when used to measure aims as it did not show the lack of progress towards the US goal of increasing South Vietnamese government control of its territory.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Another example would be to measure the productivity of a software development team in terms of lines of source code written.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] This approach can easily add large amounts of dubious code, thereby inflating the line count but adding little value in terms of systemic improvement.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] A similar problem arises when a footballer kicks a ball uselessly to build up their statistics.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Strategies to address and mitigate problems with PIs requires a thoughtful, systemic approach.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Further examples may include in nursing, replacing rigid throughput metrics with indicators that reflect quality of care, and patient experience.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] In education, balance test scores with indicators of student engagement and learning environment quality.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/performance-indicator] Finally, in public services, include metrics for community impact and equity alongside traditional efficiency indicators.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/software-metric] In software engineering and development, a **software metric** is a standard of measure of a degree to which a software system or process possesses some property.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/software-metric] Even if a metric is not a measurement (metrics are functions, while measurements are the numbers obtained by the application of metrics), often the two terms are used as synonyms.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/software-metric] Since quantitative measurements are essential in all sciences, there is a continuous effort by computer science practitioners and theoreticians to bring similar approaches to software development.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/software-metric] The goal is obtaining objective, reproducible and quantifiable measurements, which may have numerous valuable applications in schedule and budget planning, cost estimation, quality assurance, testing, software debugging, software performance optimization, and optimal personnel task assignments.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/software-metric] Another source of difficulty and debate is in determining which metrics matter, and what they mean.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/software-metric] Researchers argue that commonly used software metrics, promoted frequently in academic research, are not practically useful for software professionals' decision-making.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/software-metric] A specific measurement may target one or more of the above aspects, or the balance between them, for example as an indicator of team motivation or project performance.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/software-metric] Additionally metrics vary between static and dynamic program code, as well as for object oriented software (systems).
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/software-metric] Some software development practitioners point out that simplistic measurements can cause more harm than good.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/software-metric] Others have noted that metrics have become an integral part of the software development process.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/software-metric] Impact of measurement on programmer psychology have raised concerns for harmful effects to performance due to stress, performance anxiety, and attempts to cheat the metrics, while others find it to have positive impact on developers value towards their own work, and prevent them being undervalued.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/software-metric] Some argue that the definition of many measurement methodologies are imprecise, and consequently it is often unclear how tools for computing them arrive at a particular result, while others argue that imperfect quantification is better than none (“You can’t control what you can't measure.”).
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/software-metric] Evidence shows that software metrics are being widely used by government agencies, the US military, NASA, IT consultants, academic institutions, and commercial and academic development estimation software.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] In mathematics, a **time series** is a sequence of data points indexed, listed, or graphed in chronological order.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Most commonly, a time series consists of observations recorded at successive equally spaced points in time.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Thus, it represents a form of discrete-time data.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] A time series may describe measurements collected over seconds, days, years, or even centuries.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Common examples include heights of ocean tides, counts of sunspots, daily temperature readings, and the closing values of stock market indices such as the Dow Jones Industrial Average.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] A time series is often visualized using a run chart (a type of temporal line chart), which helps identify patterns such as trends, seasonal effects, and irregular fluctuations.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Time series data have a natural temporal ordering.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] This makes time series analysis distinct from cross-sectional studies, in which there is no natural ordering of the observations (e.g. explaining people's wages by reference to their respective education levels, where the individuals' data could be entered in any order).
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Time series analysis is also distinct from spatial data analysis where the observations typically relate to geographical locations (e.g. accounting for house prices by the location as well as the intrinsic characteristics of the houses).
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] A stochastic model for a time series will generally reflect the fact that observations close together in time will be more closely related than observations further apart.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] In addition, time series models will often make use of the natural one-way ordering of time so that values for a given period will be expressed as deriving in some way from past values, rather than from future values (see time reversibility).
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Time series analysis can be applied to real-valued, continuous data, discrete numeric data, or discrete symbolic data (i.e. sequences of characters, such as letters and words in the English language).
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Methods for time series analysis may be divided into two classes: frequency-domain methods and time-domain methods.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] The former include spectral analysis and wavelet analysis; the latter include auto-correlation and cross-correlation analysis.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] In the time domain, correlation and analysis can be made in a filter-like manner using scaled correlation, thereby mitigating the need to operate in the frequency domain.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Additionally, time series analysis techniques may be divided into parametric and non-parametric methods.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] The parametric approaches assume that the underlying stationary stochastic process has a certain structure which can be described using a small number of parameters (for example, using an autoregressive or moving-average model).
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] In these approaches, the task is to estimate the parameters of the model that describes the stochastic process.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] By contrast, non-parametric approaches explicitly estimate the covariance or the spectrum of the process without assuming that the process has any particular structure.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Methods of time series analysis may also be divided into linear and non-linear, and univariate and multivariate.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] A time series is one type of panel data.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Panel data is the general class, a multidimensional data set, whereas a time series data set is a one-dimensional panel (as is a cross-sectional dataset).
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] A data set may exhibit characteristics of both panel data and time series data.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] One way to tell is to ask what makes one data record unique from the other records.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] If the answer is the time data field, then this is a time series data set candidate.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] If determining a unique record requires a time data field and an additional identifier which is unrelated to time (e.g. student ID, stock symbol, country code), then it is panel data candidate.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] If the differentiation lies on the non-time identifier, then the data set is a cross-sectional data set candidate.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] There are several types of motivation and data analysis available for time series which are appropriate for different purposes.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] In the context of statistics, econometrics, quantitative finance, seismology, meteorology, and geophysics the primary goal of time series analysis is forecasting.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] In the context of signal processing, control engineering and communication engineering it is used for signal detection.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Other applications are in data mining, pattern recognition and machine learning, where time series analysis can be used for clustering, classification, query by content, anomaly detection as well as forecasting.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] A simple way to examine a regular time series is manually with a line chart.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] The datagraphic shows tuberculosis deaths in the United States, along with the yearly change and the percentage change from year to year.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] The total number of deaths declined in every year until the mid-1980s, after which there were occasional increases, often proportionately - but not absolutely - quite large.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] A study of corporate data analysts found two challenges to exploratory time series analysis: discovering the shape of interesting patterns, and finding an explanation for these patterns.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Visual tools that represent time series data as heat map matrices can help overcome these challenges.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] This approach may be based on harmonic analysis and filtering of signals in the frequency domain using the Fourier transform, and spectral density estimation.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Its development was significantly accelerated during World War II by mathematician Norbert Wiener, electrical engineers Rudolf E.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Kálmán, Dennis Gabor and others for filtering signals from noise and predicting signal values at a certain point in time.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] An equivalent effect may be achieved in the time domain, as in a Kalman filter; see filtering and smoothing for more techniques.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Curve fitting is the process of constructing a curve, or mathematical function, that has the best fit to a series of data points, possibly subject to constraints.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Curve fitting can involve either interpolation, where an exact fit to the data is required, or smoothing, in which a "smooth" function is constructed that approximately fits the data.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] A related topic is regression analysis, which focuses more on questions of statistical inference such as how much uncertainty is present in a curve that is fit to data observed with random errors.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Fitted curves can be used as an aid for data visualization, to infer values of a function where no data are available, and to summarize the relationships among two or more variables.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Extrapolation refers to the use of a fitted curve beyond the range of the observed data, and is subject to a degree of uncertainty since it may reflect the method used to construct the curve as much as it reflects the observed data.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] For processes that are expected to generally grow in magnitude one of the curves in the graphic (and many others) can be fitted by estimating their parameters.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] The construction of economic time series involves the estimation of some components for some dates by interpolation between values ("benchmarks") for earlier and later dates.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Interpolation is estimation of an unknown quantity between two known quantities (historical data), or drawing conclusions about missing information from the available information ("reading between the lines").
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Interpolation is useful where the data surrounding the missing data is available and its trend, seasonality, and longer-term cycles are known.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] This is often done by using a related series known for all relevant dates.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Alternatively polynomial interpolation or spline interpolation is used where piecewise polynomial functions are fitted in time intervals such that they fit smoothly together.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] A different problem which is closely related to interpolation is the approximation of a complicated function by a simple function (also called regression).
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] The main difference between regression and interpolation is that polynomial regression gives a single polynomial that models the entire data set.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Spline interpolation, however, yield a piecewise continuous function composed of many polynomials to model the data set.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Extrapolation is the process of estimating, beyond the original observation range, the value of a variable on the basis of its relationship with another variable.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] It is similar to interpolation, which produces estimates between known observations, but extrapolation is subject to greater uncertainty and a higher risk of producing meaningless results.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] In general, a function approximation problem asks us to select a function among a well-defined class that closely matches ("approximates") a target function in a task-specific way.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Second, the target function, call it *g*, may be unknown; instead of an explicit formula, only a set of points (a time series) of the form (*x*, *g*(*x*)) is provided.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Depending on the structure of the domain and codomain of *g*, several techniques for approximating *g* may be applicable.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] For example, if *g* is an operation on the real numbers, techniques of interpolation, extrapolation, regression analysis, and curve fitting can be used.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] If the codomain (range or target set) of *g* is a finite set, one is dealing with a classification problem instead.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] A related problem of *online* time series approximation is to summarize the data in one-pass and construct an approximate representation that can support a variety of time series queries with bounds on worst-case error.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] To some extent, the different problems (regression, classification, fitness approximation) have received a unified treatment in statistical learning theory, where they are viewed as supervised learning problems.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] In statistics, prediction is a part of statistical inference.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] One particular approach to such inference is known as predictive inference, but the prediction can be undertaken within any of the several approaches to statistical inference.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Indeed, one description of statistics is that it provides a means of transferring knowledge about a sample of a population to the whole population, and to other related populations, which is not necessarily the same as prediction over time.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] When information is transferred across time, often to specific points in time, the process is known as forecasting.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Assigning time series pattern to a specific category, for example identify a word based on series of hand movements in sign language.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Splitting a time-series into a sequence of segments.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] It is often the case that a time-series can be represented as a sequence of individual segments, each with its own characteristic properties.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] For example, the audio signal from a conference call can be partitioned into pieces corresponding to the times during which each person was speaking.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] In time-series segmentation, the goal is to identify the segment boundary points in the time-series, and to characterize the dynamical properties associated with each segment.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] One can approach this problem using change-point detection, or by modeling the time-series as a more sophisticated system, such as a Markov jump linear system.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Time series data may be clustered, however special care has to be taken when considering subsequence clustering.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Subsequence time series clustering resulted in unstable (random) clusters *induced by the feature extraction* using chunking with sliding windows.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] It was found that the cluster centers (the average of the time series in a cluster - also a time series) follow an arbitrarily shifted sine pattern (regardless of the dataset, even on realizations of a random walk).
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] This means that the found cluster centers are non-descriptive for the dataset because the cluster centers are always nonrepresentative sine waves.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Models for time series data can have many forms and represent different stochastic processes.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] When modeling variations in the level of a process, three broad classes of practical importance are the *autoregressive* (AR) models, the *integrated* (I) models, and the *moving-average* (MA) models.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] These three classes depend *linearly* on previous data points.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Combinations of these ideas produce autoregressive moving-average (ARMA) and autoregressive integrated moving-average (ARIMA) models.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] The autoregressive fractionally integrated moving-average (ARFIMA) model generalizes the former three.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Another important generalization is the time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) model, in which the AR coefficients are allowed to change over time, enabling the model to capture evolving or non-stationary dynamics.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Extensions of these classes to deal with vector-valued data are available under the heading of multivariate time-series models and sometimes the preceding acronyms are extended by including an initial "V" for "vector", as in VAR for vector autoregression.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] For these models, the acronyms are extended with a final "X" for "exogenous".
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) models are especially useful for analyzing non-stationary time series in which the underlying dynamics evolve over time in complex ways, not limited to classical forms of variation such as trends or seasonal patterns.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] This flexibility makes them well suited to modeling structural changes, regime shifts, or gradual evolutions in a system's behavior.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Estimation of TVAR models typically involves methods such as kernel smoothing, recursive least squares, or Kalman filtering.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Non-linear dependence of the level of a series on previous data points is of interest, partly because of the possibility of producing a chaotic time series.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] However, more importantly, empirical investigations can indicate the advantage of using predictions derived from non-linear models, over those from linear models, as for example in nonlinear autoregressive exogenous models.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Among other types of non-linear time series models, there are models to represent the changes of variance over time (heteroskedasticity).
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] These models represent autoregressive conditional heteroskedasticity (ARCH) and the collection comprises a wide variety of representation (GARCH, TARCH, EGARCH, FIGARCH, CGARCH, etc.).
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Here changes in variability are related to, or predicted by, recent past values of the observed series.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] This is in contrast to other possible representations of locally varying variability, where the variability might be modeled as being driven by a separate time-varying process, as in a doubly stochastic model.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Multiscale (often referred to as multiresolution) techniques decompose a given time series, attempting to illustrate time dependence at multiple scales.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] See also Markov switching multifractal (MSMF) techniques for modeling volatility evolution.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] A hidden Markov model (HMM) is a statistical Markov model in which the system being modeled is assumed to be a Markov process with unobserved (hidden) states.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] An HMM can be considered as the simplest dynamic Bayesian network.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] HMM models are widely used in speech recognition, for translating a time series of spoken words into text.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Many of these models are collected in the python package sktime.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] A number of different notations are in use for time-series analysis.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Ergodicity implies stationarity, but the converse is not necessarily the case.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Stationarity is usually classified into strict stationarity and wide-sense or second-order stationarity.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Both models and applications can be developed under each of these conditions, although the models in the latter case might be considered as only partly specified.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] In addition, time-series analysis can be applied where the series are seasonally stationary or non-stationary.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Situations where the amplitudes of frequency components change with time can be dealt with in time-frequency analysis which makes use of a time–frequency representation of a time-series or signal.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Time series can be visualized with two categories of chart: Overlapping Charts and Separated Charts.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] Jevons was the first to study times series.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] In his book he examined a number of weekly financial time series between the years 1825 to 1860 inclusive.
[src:micrometer-metrics-java/time-series] These included times series of bankruptcies, currency circulation and discount rates.
